   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1811_12_14_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <salute> To <persName>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName><lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1811_12_14_page02.jpg"/>
            <p>
               <persName>Miss Edgeworth's</persName> compliments<lb/> to <persName xml:id="MileX1">M<hi
                     rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName> and though a<lb/> stranger to her
               she takes the liberty<lb/> of begging the favor of her to do<lb/> a commission for
               her &amp; for M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>The present riots at <placeName>Nottingham</placeName><lb/> make them think that the
               price<lb/> of <add>British</add> lace will rise considerably &amp;<lb/> suddenly in
                  <placeName>England</placeName> &amp; before<lb/> this take place they wish to<lb/>
               buy 2 black pattinette gowns<lb/>
               <add>for</add> which they don't wish to give<lb/> more than about 3 guineas
               apiece<lb/> - If not to be had for this price<lb/> they would rather do without<lb/>
               them - If <persName xml:id="MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName> is so good<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1811_12_14_page03.jpg"/> as to undertake this
               commission M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.<lb/> &amp; Miss E beg <del>s</del>] that
               she will be good<lb/> enough to buy what will make<lb/> 2 gowns with trains and long
               sleeves<lb/> for two women about five feet high<lb/></p>
            <p>The patterns to<lb/> be a small sprig or leaf something<lb/> like the enclosed - that
               is to say<lb/> not a large <hi rend="underline">sprawling</hi> pattern<lb/> or with
               any borders which they<lb/> think vulgar - they wish to have<lb/> the <hi
                  rend="underline">ground</hi> of the <unclear>not</unclear> very fine &amp;<lb/>
               clear as that makes all the difference<lb/> in their appearances - They do not<lb/>
               care whether the gowns are exactly<lb/> the same pattern or not so that<lb/> the
               pattern of both be small -<lb/> E<lb/></p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1811_12_14_page04.jpg"/>
            <lb/>
            <p>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. They beg to have also real<lb/> black
                  <del>about</del> lace of not more than inch &amp; <add>half</add><lb/> breadth
               sufficient for the bosoms<lb/> of both gowns and narrow <hi rend="underline">to</hi><lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">match</hi> for the sleeves. -<lb/>
               <persName>M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi></persName>. and <persName>Miss
                  Edgeworth</persName><lb/> hope <persName xml:id="MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.
                  Miles</persName> will excuse<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <placeName>Edgeworth Town</placeName><lb/> Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 14<hi
                  rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1811<lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>We are not in the least hurry<lb/> to have these gowns sent over<lb/> to Ireland
                  but merely wish to<lb/> have them <hi rend="underline">bought</hi> before the<lb/>
                  price rises - In spring we will<lb/> desire a friend to call for them &amp; bring
                  them over<lb/></p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
